@phdthesis{gibbonsStrategiesDesignReflective2020,
  title = {Strategies for the Design of Reflective Shortform Videogames},
  author = {Gibbons, Liam},
  year = {2020},
  abstract = {{$<$}p{$>$}Through the critical, iterative making of a series of game design experiments, in this practice-based research I enact and interrogate a collection of strategies and terms for the design, making, study, and discussion of reflective, shortform videogames. These are videogames, generally produced by individuals or small teams of makers, that are designed to be experienced in a single sitting, and encourage players to thoughtfully consider, reflect upon, anticipate, and configure the audiovisual, narrative, and/or ludic elements juxtaposed within the game's digital-virtual space. Historically, there have been a series of shortform game designs that are invested in offering the player an intense, reaction-based challenge. Recently however, a variety of non-commercial game designers have been experimenting with and producing shortform videogames that instead seek to elicit reflective forms of play. These designers, including myself, have been spurred on by the increasing accessibility and availability of game development tools and online distribution platforms. Much formal and informal game design knowledge fails to account for this emerging form, and instead assumes either a long form, or a design goal of immediate, reaction-based play within a short form.{$<$}/p{$>$} {$<$}p{$>$}Seeking to address this gap in knowledge, in this research I offer game designers four key strategies for the design of reflective play within a shortform game design. They include limiting, omitting, and making ambiguous traditional elements of game design such as objectives and win/lose conditions, and avoiding any interruptions or excessive direction to the player's experience of the game. Crucially, I suggest that it is useful to pair this with strictly limited, clear and consistent spatiotemporal barriers and boundaries. This reduces the scope of the game design to a single spatial cell that is experienced near-simultaneously. I uncover, articulate, and demonstrate these strategies through the design and making of ten game design experiments. This is an exploratory process supported by critical reflection, reading and writing. Each game investigates some aspect of reflective and/or brief game design, and together they reveal a set of subjective, situated tactics for encouraging reflective play within a shortform videogame.{$<$}/p{$>$}},
  keywords = {Game design,Game studies,Practice-based research,Reflective play,Short form}
}

